===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|heelden}}, {{m|enm|helden}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|hieldan}}, {{m|ang|heldan||to lean, incline, slope, force downwards, bow or bend down}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*halþijaną||to bend, incline, pour, empty}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*kel-||to tilt, tip, incline}}. Cognate with {{cog|nl|hellen||to incline}}, {{cog|nds|hellen||to incline}}, {{cog|gmh|helden||to incline}}, {{cog|da|hælde||to tilt, lean, slant, slope}}, {{cog|sv|hälla||to tilt, pour}}, {{cog|is|halla||incline, lean sideways, heel over}}, {{cog|is|hella||to pur}}. See also {{l|en|heel}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[bend]]; [[incline]]; [[tilt]] (as a water-vessel or ship); [[heel]].
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[pour out]]; [[pour]].
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[throw]]; [[cast]]; [[put]].
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[bow]]; bend; incline; tilt or [[cant]] over.
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[decline]]; [[sink]]; go down.
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[yield]]; give way; [[surrender]].

